MCMCglmm

The output of the MCMCglmm() function include :

  • Sol : Posterior Distribution of MME solutions, including fixed effects [posterior distribution of the estimates of fixed and random effects]

  • VCV : Posterior Distribution of (co)variance matrices [posterior distribution of the variances]

  • CP :Posterior Distribution of cut-points from an ordinal model

  • Liab : Posterior Distribution of latent variables

  • Fixed : list: fixed formula and number of fixed effects

  • Random : list: random formula, dimensions of each covariance matrix, number of levels per covariance matrix, and term in random formula to which each covariance belongs

  • Residual : list: residual formula, dimensions of each covariance matrix, number of levels per covariance matrix, and term in residual formula to which each covariance belongs

  • Deviance : deviance -2*log(p(y|…))

  • DIC : deviance information criterion

  • X : sparse fixed effect design matrix

  • Z : sparse random effect design matrix

  • XL: sparse structural parameter design matrix

  • error.term : residual term for each datum

  • family : distribution of each datum

  • Tune :(co)variance matrix of the proposal distribution for the latent variables

  • pl : boolean (default : F), if sotrage of latent variables (e.g. \(E[y]\)) posterior distribution

  • pr : boolean (default : F), if sotrage of the posterior distribution of random effects

NOTE : in MCMCglmm output, the units in the summary refers to the residuals.

## Model X (PUPS) ____________ ### Model construction Prior distribution of random effect

prior <- list(R = list(V = diag(2), nu = 2),  # prior for residual variance
              G = list(G1 = list(V = diag(2), nu = 2, alpha.mu = rep(0, 2), alpha.V = 1000*diag(2)),  # animal
                       G2 = list(V = diag(2), nu = 2, alpha.mu = rep(0, 2), alpha.V = 1000*diag(2)),  # cohort
                       G3 = list(V = diag(2), nu = 2, alpha.mu = rep(0, 2), alpha.V = 1000*diag(2))  # mother
              )
)


Model

# META PARAMETERS
sample_size_goal <- 1000
burnin = 300000
thin = 5000
nitt = thin * sample_size_goal + burnin

paste0("Effective iteration : ", nitt)


data <- data_mcmc_biv_marmotton

# --- Remove cohort with < 3 observations
data <- data[!data$annee_emergence %in% c(1990:1996),]
data$annee_emergence <- factor(data$annee_emergence, levels = c(1997:2023))


# GAM FOR COHORT ----------------------------------------------------------
data[,"annee_emergence_gam"] <- as.numeric(as.character(data[,"annee_emergence"]))


# NORMALIZATION
data[,"annee_emergence_gam"]  = as.numeric(data[,"annee_emergence"]) - min(as.numeric(data[,"annee_emergence"]))
data[,"annee_emergence_gam"] <- data[,"annee_emergence_gam"] / max(data[,"annee_emergence_gam"])

# CUBIC SPLINES
n.knots <- 3
X <- cubic_spline(covariable = as.numeric(data[,"annee_emergence_gam"]), n.knots = n.knots)$X  # see FUNCTIONS.R for cubic_spline()

# MERGE X WITH DATA
data <- cbind(data, X)



# SCALE PREDICTORS --------------------------------------------------------
fixed_effects <- c("capture_time", "age_d", "litter_size_naissance", "taille_groupe_naissance", "inbreeding")

# --- Non GAM fixed effects
for(i in fixed_effects){
  data[,i] <- scale(data[,i], center = TRUE, scale = FALSE)
}

# --- GAM fixed effect [we scale them also as units does not matter]
gam__fixed_effects <- paste0("V", 2:(n.knots+2))

for(i in gam__fixed_effects){
  data[,i] <- scale(data[,i], center = TRUE, scale = TRUE)
}

# PRUNED PEDIGREE ---------------------------------------------------------
pedigree <- prunePed(pedigree = pedigree_data_biv_marmotton[1:3],
                     keep = data$individual_id,  # IDs of informative individual and descendant (i.e. with measures)
                     make.base = T)

# PRIOR DEFINITION --------------------------------------------------------
prior <- list(R = list(V = diag(2), nu = 2),  # prior for residual variance
              G = list(G1 = list(V = diag(2), nu = 2, alpha.mu = rep(0, 2), alpha.V = 1000*diag(2)),  # animal
                       G2 = list(V = diag(2), nu = 2, alpha.mu = rep(0, 2), alpha.V = 1000*diag(2)),  # anne_emergence
                       G3 = list(V = diag(2), nu = 2, alpha.mu = rep(0, 2), alpha.V = 1000*diag(2))  # mother
              )
)


# MODEL -------------------------------------------------------------------
mod_tibia_mcmc_13triv_1997 <- MCMCglmm(
  data = data,
  fixed = cbind(masse, tibia) ~ 
    (trait - 1) +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia", "masse")):capture_time+
    at.level(trait, c("tibia", "masse")):sexe +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia", "masse")):age_d +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia", "masse")):litter_size_naissance +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia", "masse")):taille_groupe_naissance +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia", "masse")):inbreeding +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia", "masse")):V2 +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia")):V3 +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia")):V4 +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia")):V5,
  
  random = ~ us(trait):animal + us(trait):annee_emergence + us(trait):mother,
  rcov = ~ us(trait):units,
  nitt = nitt,
  burnin = burnin,
  family = c("gaussian", "gaussian"),
  thin = thin,
  pedigree = pedigree,
  pr = T,  # get bv
  prior = prior,
  verbose = F
)

Coefficient of variation

# FUNCTION
coef_var <- function(trait = "tibia", variance, data = data_mcmc_biv_marmotton, title = NULL){
  cat("\n ==========", title ,"============ \n ")
  mean_trait <- mean(data[,trait], na.rm = T)
  cv <- round(100 * mean(sqrt(variance) / mean_trait), 2)
  cv_lwr <- round(HPDinterval(100 *sqrt(variance) / mean_trait)[1], 2)
  cv_upr <- round(HPDinterval(100 *sqrt(variance) / mean_trait)[2], 2)
  
  return(cat(trait, " : ", cv, " [",cv_lwr, "; ", cv_upr, "]\n"))
}

SELECTION MODEL

Model FITNESS (PUPS) ____________

# META PARAMETERS
sample_size_goal <- 1000
burnin = 300000
thin = 6000
nitt = thin * sample_size_goal + burnin

paste0("Effective iteration : ", nitt)


# DATA USED
data <- data_mcmc_biv_marmotton

# SELECT COHORT FOR WHICH FITNESS CAN BE CALCULATED -----------------------
# AGE THRESHOLD DETERMINED PREVIOUSLY FROM WHICH WE CONSIDER THE COHORT IS EXTINCT
age_threshold <- 7
data <- data[!data$annee_emergence %in% c(1990, 1991, 1996, (2023-age_threshold + 1):2023),]
data$annee_emergence <- factor(data$annee_emergence, levels = c(1992:1995, 1997:(2023-age_threshold)))




# COMPUTE FITNESS ---------------------------------------------------------
pheno <- pheno[!duplicated(pheno$individual_id),]  # only non repeated individual of the whole dataset 
mean_cohort_LRS <- tapply(pheno$LRS, pheno$annee_emergence, function(x) mean(x, na.rm = T))  # get mean LRS per cohort
index <- match(data$annee_emergence, names(mean_cohort_LRS))  # get index to divide LRS of dataset with associated cohort LRS mean
data["LRS_relative"] <- data$LRS / mean_cohort_LRS[index]



# GAM FOR COHORT ----------------------------------------------------------
# CONVERT VI TO NUMERIC
data[,"annee_emergence_gam"] <- as.numeric(as.character(data[,"annee_emergence"]))


# NORMALIZATION
data[,"annee_emergence_gam"]  = as.numeric(data[,"annee_emergence"]) - min(as.numeric(data[,"annee_emergence"]))
data[,"annee_emergence_gam"] <- data[,"annee_emergence_gam"] / max(data[,"annee_emergence_gam"])

# CUBIC SPLINES
n.knots <- 3
X <- cubic_spline(covariable = as.numeric(data[,"annee_emergence_gam"]), n.knots = n.knots)$X

# MERGE X WITH DATA
data <- cbind(data, X)


# SCALE PREDICTORS --------------------------------------------------------
fixed_effects <- c("capture_time", "age_d", "litter_size_naissance", "taille_groupe_naissance", "inbreeding")

# --- Non GAM fixed effects
for(i in fixed_effects){
  data[,i] <- scale(data[,i], center = TRUE, scale = FALSE)
}

# --- GAM fixed effect [we scale them also as units does not matter]
gam__fixed_effects <- paste0("V", 2:(n.knots + 2))

for(i in gam__fixed_effects){
  data[,i] <- scale(data[,i], center = TRUE, scale = TRUE)
}


# PRUNED PEDIGREE ---------------------------------------------------------
pedigree <- prunePed(pedigree = pedigree_data_biv_marmotton[1:3],
                     keep = data$individual_id,  # IDs of informative individual and descendant (i.e. with measures)
                     make.base = T)


# PRIOR DEFINITION --------------------------------------------------------
prior <- list(R = list(V = diag(3), nu = 3),  # prior for residual variance
              G = list(G1 = list(V = diag(3), nu = 3, alpha.mu = rep(0, 3), alpha.V = 1000*diag(3)),  # animal
                       G2 = list(V = diag(2), nu = 2, alpha.mu = rep(0, 2), alpha.V = 1000*diag(2)),  # annee_emergence
                       G3 = list(V = diag(3), nu = 3, alpha.mu = rep(0, 3), alpha.V = 1000*diag(3))  # mother
              )
)


# MODEL -------------------------------------------------------------------
mod_tibia_mcmc_13triv_fitness <- MCMCglmm(
  data = data,
  fixed = cbind(tibia, masse, LRS_relative) ~ 
    (trait - 1) +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia", "masse")):capture_time+
    at.level(trait, c("tibia", "masse")):sexe +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia", "masse")):age_d +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia", "masse")):litter_size_naissance +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia", "masse")):taille_groupe_naissance +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia", "masse")):inbreeding +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia", "masse")):V2 +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia")):V3 +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia")):V4 +
    at.level(trait, c("tibia")):V5,
  
  random = ~ us(trait):animal + us(at.level(trait, c("tibia", "masse"))):annee_emergence + us(trait):mother,
  rcov = ~ us(trait):units,
  nitt = nitt,
  burnin = burnin,
  family = c("gaussian", "gaussian", "gaussian"),
  thin = thin,
  pedigree = pedigree,
  pr = T,  # get bv
  prior = prior,  
  verbose = F
)

# SAVE RESULTS
save(mod_tibia_mcmc_13triv_fitness, file = "~/TIBIA/SORTIE_MODELES/mod13triv_fitness.rds")

Selection parameters and prediction of response to selection

The selection differential (S) [predictive rate of evolutionnary change] is equal to the sum of additive genetic and environemental covariance between trait and fitness. The selection gradient (B) corresponds to the slope of the regression fitness ~ trait and is computed as S / Var(P). The selection differential measure total selection while selection gradient measure direct selection only (linear selection).
